colin@nyx10.cs.du.edu (Colin Plumb) writes:

>It's a matter of U.S. law, and it makes it illegal to export cryptographic
>software from the U.S.  Once it's out, however, there are no encumbrances.
>Even the U.S. mostly (Panama and Mexico have observed exceptions :-()
>recognizes that its laws only apply within their borders.


[site list deleted]
>>
>>QUESTION3: Can I legally use these programs after FTPing them?

>Any software (e.g. not rsa.com:pub/faq, which is text) that performs
>encryption (I don't think beta.xerox.com:pub/hash counts) is illegal to
>export from the U.S.  without a pile of paperwork which may or may not
>get approved.

>So I'd avoid ftp.uu.net, rsa.com and ripem.msu.edu if you care about U.S.
>law.  Note that you're not obligated to, and even if the U.S. were to
>fuss if you ever travelled to within its jurisdiction (low probability;
>when I left the U.S. last year with crypto source code, two customs agents
>(Detroit and Peace Bridge, NY) advised me to junk the paperwork I was
>trying to file with them and just *go*; I had to spend 20 minutes with the
>ITAR explaining), they'd have a hard time proving it was really you.

ripem.msu.edu--and probably the other "official" U.S. sites--require you to
certify that you are a U.S. citizen and agree to abide by export control 
regulations before granting you access to controlled code. 

>Still, it would be polite to the site admins not to give them any
>reason to be hassled by the export control people.  But the basic
>summary is, you aren't in the U.S., so the stupid laws don't apply to
>you.  Forget about them.
>-- 
>	-Colin
